The week ahead: collect seed and control clematis Helen Yemm's quick tips for the garden this week. Now is the time to remove algae from your pond Photo: ALAMY By Helen Yemm
6:30AM BST 06 Aug 2012
Comments
Prune shrub roses
Cut back the shoots that have done their thing, preserving the new shoots. Mature specimens will need more pruning in winter.
Collect seed Collect ripened seed of sweet cicely, angelica and Smyrnium perfoliatum. Seed of these plants germinates best if sown straight away.
Control clematis
Related Articles
Thorny problems: Can I plant clematis in summer?
26 Jul 2012
What to do this week: snip lilies and attack aquilegias
26 Jul 2012
Thorny problems: a troublesome hedge and Spring shrub rescue
06 Aug 2012
Snip off long wayward extremities of Clematis montana. Shoots produced thereafter should be left alone.
Remove algae Haul out blanket weed from ponds by twisting it around a stick. Throw some watercress in the water, which helps “eat” the algae-causing nutrients.
Trim cosmos
Use a fine afternoon to deadhead cosmos, and thereby ensure a long, long, display of flowers.
