Peter Smith
Peter Smith, who has died aged 86, was an architectural historian and author of Houses of the Welsh Countryside, a book which has had a profound influence on the understanding and appreciation of domestic architecture in the Principality since its publication in 1975.
Peter Smith 6:00PM BST 01 Apr 2013
Comments
A member of staff of the Royal Commission on Ancient and Historical Monuments in Wales and Monmouthshire, Smith was inspired to write the book while he was carrying out emergency recording of threatened buildings in Wales and came across a tumbledown barn, rotting away in a remote valley in mid-Wales. What he found when he went up closer was a timber frame with a few shreds and patches of wall and roof. He immediately recognised it as an aisled hall of the 1400s, built from the magnificent oaks that then proliferated in the Severn valley — a building which reflected the prestige of the Welsh aristocracy six centuries ago.
The importance and vulnerability of the structure, known as Ty Mawr, started Smith on a project that would see it restored to its former glory and inspire the saving of many other gems of Welsh domestic architecture. From the early medieval house and the longhouse to houses of the Welsh border, through to the cottage and the modern house, Smith’s lavishly illustrated Houses of the Welsh Countryside, published by the Royal Commission, was based on the close examination of thousands of old houses, many of them difficult to access, and informed by a study of documentary sources, particularly probate inventories and church terriers. The book was awarded the Alice Davis Hitchcock Medallion of the Society of Architectural Historians.
Had Smith not brought Ty Mawr to public attention, the building could easily have gone the way of Plas Cadwgan, a magnificent late 14th-century aisled hall that had later belonged to Edward Jones, master of the wardrobe to Elizabeth I, but was dismissed as “strange looking” and demolished in 1967. Instead, with subsequent restoration, Ty Mawr defeated Tate Modern to receive the Royal Institute of Chartered Surveyors’ Building of the Year award in 2000.
The son of a schools’ inspector, Peter Smith was born on June 15 1926 at Winlaton-on-Tyne, Co Durham, and educated at King Edward VI School, Southampton, from where he won the Hampshire Open Scholarship to Oxford to read Modern History.
After graduation and a brief period working at the Ministry of Transport, he studied for and passed the Intermediate Examination of the Royal Institute of British Architects, and in 1949 was appointed to the Royal Commission on Ancient and Historical Monuments in Wales and Monmouthshire (later the Royal Commission on the Ancient and Historical Monuments of Wales). There he embarked on a long professional study of Welsh antiquities and was appointed Secretary to the Commission in 1973. In the immediate post-war period the Commission staff (the Secretary and four investigators) all worked on monuments of every period. However, encouraged by Sir Cyril Fox, keeper of archaeology at the National Museum of Wales, Smith developed a particular interest in the interpretation of historic farmhouses and other vernacular structures. He would become an early member of the Vernacular Architecture Group, serving as its president.
This interest was evident early on in his contribution to the Caernarvonshire Inventory and in his investigations of the stone houses of Glamorgan. The opportunity for a broader study of Welsh architecture was presented by the transfer of the National Buildings Record to the Commission in 1963, when he was moved from inventory work to the emergency recording of threatened buildings throughout Wales, including timber-built houses. Smith’s provisional views on the development of vernacular architecture were published in 1967 as a chapter on “Rural Housing in Wales” in The Agrarian History of England and Wales, 1500-1640, and then developed into his Houses of the Welsh Countryside.
After his retirement in 1991, Smith continued to research and write, and in 2010 was behind a Welsh-language television series for S4C about the history of domestic architecture in Wales. Peter Smith is survived by his wife, Joyce, and by their three children.
Peter Smith, born June 15 1926, died March 12 2013 Obituaries
